{"cursor":"3858","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Johann Jacob Dillenius image = Johann Jakob Dillenius.jpg image_size =\n| alt = caption = Johann Jacob Dillenius birth_date = 1687 birth_place =\n| Darmstadt, Hesse-Darmstadt death_date = death_place = Oxford, England\n| residence = citizenship = nationality = German ethnicity = fields = workplaces\n| = Oxford University alma_mater = University of Giessen\n}} 'Johann Jacob Dillen Dillenius' (1687â2 April 1747) was a German botanist.\n\nDillen was born at Darmstadt and was educated at the University of Giessen,\nwhere he wrote several botanical papers for the Ephemerides naturae curiosorum,\nand printed, in 1719, his Catalogus plantarum sponte circa Gissam nascentium,\nillustrated with figures drawn and engraved by his own hand, and containing\ndescriptions of many new species. In 1721, at the instance of the botanist\nWilliam Sherard (1659â1728), he moved to England, and in 1724 he published a new\nedition of John Ray's Synopsis Methodica Stirpium Britannicarum. In 1732 he\npublished Hortus Elthamensis, a catalogue of the rare plants growing at Eltham,\nLondon, in the collection of Sherard's younger brother, James (1666â1738), who,\nafter making a fortune as an apothecary, devoted himself to gardening and music.\nFor this work Dillen himself executed 324 plates, and it was described by\nLinnaeus, who spent a month with him at Oxford in 1736, and afterwards dedicated\nhis Critica botanica to him, as opus botanicum quo absolutius mundus non vidit.\nLinnaeus would later name a genus of tropical tree [[Dillenia]] in his honor. In\n1734 Dillenius was appointed Sherardian professor of botany at Oxford, in\naccordance with the will of W. Sherard, who at his death in 1728 left the\nuniversity 3000 pounds for the endowment of the chair, as well as his library\nand herbarium, all on the condition that Dillenius should be appointed the first\nprofessor.\n\nDillen, who was also the author of an Historia muscorum (1741), died at Oxford,\nof apoplexy. His manuscripts, books and collections of dried plants, with many\ndrawings, were bought by his successor at Oxford, Dr. Humphry Sibthorp\n(1713â1797), and ultimately passed into the possession of Oxford University. For\nan account of his collections preserved at Oxford, see The Dillenian Herbaria,\nby G. Claridge Druce (Oxford, 1907).\n\nThe standard author abbreviation 'Dill.' is applied to species he described.\n","linknr":146,"url":"Johann_Jacob_Dillenius","recorded":1376425371,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Johann_Jacob_Dillenius&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Johann_Jacob_Dillenius&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johann_Jacob_Dillenius","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.visualEditor.viewPageTarget.noscript&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/File:Johann_Jakob_Dillenius.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/12/Johann_Jakob_Dillenius.jpg/220px-Johann_Jakob_Dillenius.jpg","/wiki/Darmstadt","/wiki/Landgraviate_of_Hesse-Darmstadt","/wiki/Oxford","/wiki/England","/wiki/Germany","/wiki/Botany","/wiki/Oxford_University","/wiki/Alm